    <h2>Key Factors When Buying a Bread Slicer in India</h2>

    <h3>Loaf Dimensions</h3>
    <p>The most critical specification. Your bread slicer must accommodate your loaf's dimensions — length, width, and height. Standard bread tins in India produce loaves approximately 18–24 cm long, 10–12 cm wide, and 12–14 cm tall. Measure your loaves before purchasing. A slicer that can't fit your loaf is useless.</p>

    <h3>Slice Thickness</h3>
    <p>Most commercial bread slicers offer slice thickness options of 12mm (thin/sandwich slices), 19mm (toast slices), and some offer 25mm (thick/Texas toast). If you sell different slice thicknesses, look for a slicer with quick-change thickness settings.</p>

    <h3>Blade Material and Count</h3>
    <p>High-quality bread slicers use hardened stainless steel blades. The number of blades equals the number of slices produced per cycle — typically 18–20 blades for a standard loaf. Better-quality blades stay sharper longer and produce cleaner cuts with fewer crumbs.</p>

    <h3>Crumb Tray</h3>
    <p>Look for slicers with a slide-out crumb tray for easy cleaning. Bread crumbs accumulated in the slicer are both a hygiene issue and a fire hazard if they contact heating elements. FSSAI commercial kitchens require regular cleaning of food-contact surfaces.</p>

    <h3>Safety Features</h3>
    <p>Bread slicers are dangerous — the blades are extremely sharp. Look for: blade guards that prevent hand contact with blades, automatic shut-off when the guard is removed, and CE/safety certification marks.</p>

