    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the price of a bread slicer machine in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Bread slicer machine prices in India range from ₹8,000 for a basic manual gravity slicer to ₹5 lakh or more for a fully automatic industrial bread slicer. For most small-to-medium bakeries, a semi-automatic slicer priced ₹35,000 – ₹80,000 is the practical choice.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How many loaves per hour can a commercial bread slicer handle? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A manual slicer handles 240–480 loaves per hour. A semi-automatic slicer handles 600–1,200 loaves per hour. A fully automatic slicer handles 1,800–7,200+ loaves per hour. For a bakery producing 200 loaves per day, a basic semi-automatic slicer is more than sufficient.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How often should I replace bread slicer blades? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Commercial bread slicer blades should be sharpened every 3–6 months under heavy use, and replaced when sharpening no longer restores cutting efficiency (typically every 2–5 years depending on usage and bread type). Blades that are too dull squash rather than cut, creating ragged slices and excessive crumbing.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can a bread slicer handle all types of bread? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Most commercial bread slicers are optimised for standard sandwich/tin loaves. Very fresh bread (under-cooled) squashes and doesn't slice cleanly — bread should cool to room temperature before slicing. Dense, heavy breads (like pumpernickel) need more robust slicers. Artisan breads with very hard crusts can wear blades quickly. Always specify your bread types when consulting with a supplier.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Is a bread slicer necessary for a small bakery? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Only if you sell pre-sliced bread. If you sell whole loaves that customers slice at home, you don't need one. If you supply supermarkets, canteens, or institutional customers who require pre-sliced and packaged bread, a slicer is essential. Manual slicers are adequate for small volumes at low cost. As production grows past 50 loaves per day, a semi-automatic slicer pays for itself in time savings.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

